public class Interner<T>
extends Object

Canonicalizes objects. Given an object, the intern() method returns a canonical representation of that object, that is, an object which equals() the input. Furthermore, given two objects x and y, it is guaranteed that if x.equals(y), then intern(x) == intern(y). The default behavior is that the interner is backed by a HashMap and the canonical version of an object x is simply the first object that equals(x) which is passed to the interner. In this case, it can be true that intern(x) == x. The backing map can be specified by passing a MapFactory on construction (though the only standard option which makes much sense is the WeakHashMap, which is slower than a HashMap, but which allows unneeded keys to be reclaimed by the garbage collector). The source of canonical elements can be changed by specifying an Interner.Factory on construction.
